# Section 9 — Complete End-to-End Request Lifecycle

---

# 9.1 Introduction

Understanding the architecture and individual MCP servers is only part of the story.

The real power of the Study Abroad Finder lies in how all components collaborate to solve a single user request.

This section traces the complete lifecycle of a request from the moment a user types a question until the final response appears on the screen.

Rather than viewing the application as individual files, we now examine it as a living system where multiple layers cooperate.

This chapter serves as the bridge between architecture and execution.

---

# 9.2 Example User Request

Assume a student enters the following query:

> "I want to study Artificial Intelligence in Germany. Suggest the best universities, scholarships, visa requirements, cost of living, current weather, nearby attractions, and generate a report."

This single sentence requires multiple reasoning steps and multiple tool invocations.

---

# 9.3 Overall Execution Flow

```
Student

↓

Browser

↓

Flask UI

↓

server.py

↓

run_query(question)

↓

agent.py

↓

Google ADK

↓

Gemini 2.5 Flash

↓

Reasoning

↓

Tool Selection

↓

MCP Servers

↓

Collect Results

↓

Generate Final Response

↓

Flask

↓

Browser

↓

Student
```

Everything begins with one sentence from the user.

---

# 9.4 Step 1 — User Interaction

The student opens the web application.

```
https://genai-agent-gcp-mcp-adk.onrender.com
```

The browser displays the Study Abroad Finder interface.

The user enters a question into the input field.

Example:

```
AI in Germany
```

or

```
Machine Learning in USA
```

or

```
Data Science in Canada
```

No AI processing has started yet.

---

# 9.5 Step 2 — Browser Sends Request

When the user clicks

```
Find Universities
```

JavaScript sends

```
POST /ask
```

to Flask.

Example payload

```json
{
    "question": "AI in Germany"
}
```

The browser now waits for a response.

---

# 9.6 Step 3 — Flask Receives Request

Flask receives the HTTP request.

```
server.py
```

extracts the question.

Example

```python
question = request.form["question"]
```

The Flask layer performs no reasoning.

Its responsibility is only routing.

---

# 9.7 Step 4 — Transfer to AI Layer

Flask calls

```python
run_query(question)
```

This transfers control from

Presentation Layer

↓

AI Layer

Everything beyond this point is handled by Google ADK.

---

# 9.8 Step 5 — Session Creation

Inside

```
agent.py
```

Google ADK creates a session.

```
Session

↓

User

↓

Conversation

↓

Context
```

Example

```python
session_service.create_session(...)
```

Every conversation belongs to a session.

Sessions allow the AI system to maintain context during execution.

---

# 9.9 Step 6 — Runner Initialization

ADK creates a Runner.

```
Runner

↓

Coordinates Execution

↓

Controls Gemini

↓

Controls Tool Calls
```

The Runner becomes responsible for the remainder of the workflow.

---

# 9.10 Step 7 — Structured Message Creation

The user question is converted into a structured ADK message.

Example

```python
types.Content(
    role="user",
    parts=[
        types.Part(text=question)
    ]
)
```

Instead of sending plain text,

ADK sends structured content.

---

# 9.11 Step 8 — Gemini Receives the Prompt

Gemini now receives:

- User Question
- Agent Instructions
- Available Tools

Gemini begins reasoning.

At this point,

Gemini has not called any MCP server.

It is only deciding

"What information do I need?"

---

# 9.12 Step 9 — Internal Reasoning

Gemini analyzes the request.

Example reasoning

```
Need Universities

↓

Need Scholarships

↓

Need Visa

↓

Need Cost

↓

Need Weather

↓

Need Nearby Attractions

↓

Need Markdown Report
```

Gemini converts the natural language request into a sequence of tool requirements.

---

# 9.13 Step 10 — Tool Planning

Gemini determines which tools can satisfy each requirement.

```
Universities

↓

Tavily MCP

------------------

Scholarships

↓

Scholarship MCP

------------------

Visa

↓

Scholarship MCP

------------------

Cost of Living

↓

Scholarship MCP

------------------

Weather

↓

Google Maps MCP

------------------

Nearby Places

↓

Google Maps MCP

------------------

Save Report

↓

Filesystem MCP
```

This planning step is entirely automatic.

No manual routing logic exists in the application.

---

# 9.14 Step 11 — ADK Creates MCP Sessions

Google ADK now begins creating MCP sessions.

```
ADK

↓

Open Tavily Session

↓

Open Scholarship Session

↓

Open Maps Session

↓

Open Filesystem Session
```

Each MCP server operates independently.

---

# 9.15 Step 12 — MCP Server Execution

Each server executes its specialized task.

Example

```
Tavily

↓

Search Universities

↓

Return Rankings
```

```
Scholarship

↓

Find Scholarships

↓

Return Results
```

```
Maps

↓

Weather

↓

Nearby Places

↓

Return Results
```

```
Filesystem

↓

Write Markdown

↓

Save Report

↓

Return Success
```

Each MCP server remains unaware of the others.

---

# 9.16 Step 13 — ADK Collects Results

Google ADK receives structured outputs from every MCP server.

```
Universities

Scholarships

Visa

Weather

Nearby Places

Markdown Saved
```

These are returned as structured tool outputs.

---

# 9.17 Step 14 — Gemini Synthesizes the Answer

Now Gemini performs its second reasoning phase.

Instead of asking

"What do I need?"

Gemini asks

"How do I explain these results?"

Gemini combines

- Tavily output
- Scholarship output
- Maps output
- Filesystem status

into one coherent response.

---

# 9.18 Step 15 — Final Response Event

Runner continues processing events.

Many internal events occur:

```
Tool Started

↓

Tool Finished

↓

Session Updated

↓

Intermediate Events
```

Only one event is

```
Final Response
```

The application ignores all other events.

---

# 9.19 Step 16 — Response Returns to Flask

Google ADK returns

```
Final Text
```

to

```
server.py
```

Flask converts it into JSON.

Example

```json
{
    "answer": "Here are the top universities..."
}
```

---

# 9.20 Step 17 — Browser Displays Result

The browser receives

```
HTTP 200
```

and updates the page.

The student now sees

- Universities
- Scholarships
- Visa
- Weather
- Nearby Attractions

along with confirmation that the report has been generated.

