# 9.22 Failure Handling

During development, the lifecycle also helped explain failures.

Examples:

If the Filesystem MCP could not start:

```
Gemini

↓

Filesystem Tool

↓

Session Creation Failed

↓

ADK Waits

↓

Request Timeout
```

If Google Maps authentication failed:

```
Gemini

↓

Maps Tool

↓

Authentication Error

↓

Tool Failure

↓

Partial Response
```

Tracing failures through the lifecycle made debugging significantly easier.

---

# 9.23 Architectural Insight

One of the most important observations from this project is that the language model never performs the external work itself.

Gemini only reasons.

Google ADK orchestrates.

MCP servers execute.

External systems provide domain-specific information.

This separation creates a modular architecture in which reasoning and execution remain independent.

---

# 9.24 Key Takeaways

The complete request lifecycle demonstrates how multiple independent components collaborate to satisfy a single user request.

A simple question from the user is transformed into:

- Structured reasoning
- Automatic tool selection
- Multiple MCP invocations
- Aggregated results
- Report generation
- Natural language synthesis

The user experiences a single conversational interaction, while internally the application coordinates several independent services through Google ADK and the Model Context Protocol.

This execution model represents the core architectural pattern of modern tool-augmented AI systems and serves as the foundation for scalable enterprise AI applications.